com.apriori.collections

Class ArrayBlockingDeque<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • com.apriori.collections.AbstractDeque<E>
          • com.apriori.collections.AbstractLockFreeBlockingDeque<E>
            • com.apriori.collections.ArrayBlockingDeque<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements held in the queue
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, BlockingDeque<E>, BlockingQueue<E>, Deque<E>, Queue<E>

    public class ArrayBlockingDeque<E>
extends AbstractLockFreeBlockingDeque<E>
    A double-ended blocking queue backed by an array. This class uses two locks, one each for the head and tail of the deque. It is not lock-free, but extends AbstractLockFreeBlockingDeque in order to inherit its custom wait/notify mechanisms. Typical lock Condition queues won't work since there are two locks which could generate "not empty" and "not full" notices.

    Operations on one side of the queue typically only need to acquire one of the locks. But removing the last element requires both locks since the last element is both the head and tail of the queue. The first element added will be the head and the tail, too, but adding the first element can actually be done safely from either end without holding both locks. This is because the two additions don't actually contend over the same slot in the underlying array: adding via tail uses the slot after the one used by adding via head.

    Because there is no single lock for the whole array, operations can only operate on the head or tail (holding the respective lock). Therefore this implementation does not support interior removes. So calls to remove(Object), removeAll(Collection), retainAll(Collection), Collection.removeIf(Predicate), and Iterator.remove() will throw UnsupportedOperationException. This makes the queue most suitable for custom usages that will never attempt an interior remove.

    The lack of support for interior removals rules out usage with a ThreadPoolExecutor, which does attempt interior removes for some operations (including ThreadPoolExecutor.execute(Runnable)). For a high-performance executor work queue that is backed by an array, instead consider LockFreeArrayBlockingQueue.executorWorkQueue(int).
